# Changelog

All notable changes to DINOForge will be documented in this file.

The format is based on [Keep a Changelog](https://keepachangelog.com/en/1.1.0/),
and this project adheres to [Semantic Versioning](https://semver.org/spec/v2.0.0.html).

## [Unreleased]

### Fixed — AssetSwap: `hasArchetypeFilter` re-resolution disagreed with the query's own narrowing (#986 final)
- **Symptom:** Swaps logged `swapped 0/100 entities (total matching=193, skipped 0 non-matching meshes)` even though the EntityQuery had successfully narrowed to the right archetype (`filtering by 'Components.MeleeUnit' for vanilla_mapping='line_infantry'`). The hand-guessed mesh-name substrings (`Soldier`/`Infantry`/...) stayed active as a reject filter.
- **Root cause (the mismatch):** `TrySwapRenderMeshFromBundle` resolved the archetype ONCE up front (setting `resolvedArchetypeType` and building the narrowed query, ~L646-661), then computed `hasArchetypeFilter` from a SEPARATE second resolution (`TryResolveSwapArchetype(...) && ResolveTypeByName(...) != null`, ~L886-889). The two resolutions could disagree (live: query path TRUE, re-resolution FALSE), so the `if (hasArchetypeFilter) targetMeshSubstrings = null;` guard never fired and the substring reject-filter dropped matched entities.
- **Fix (`src/Runtime/Bridge/AssetSwapSystem.cs` ~L886):** `hasArchetypeFilter` now reads the single source of truth — `resolvedArchetypeType != null` — the exact value the EntityQuery used to narrow. When the query was archetype-narrowed, substrings are nulled and every matched entity is swapped; the DIAGNOSTIC-MODE safety (active only when NEITHER archetype NOR substrings exist) is unchanged. Build: `dotnet build src/Runtime/DINOForge.Runtime.csproj -c Release -p:TargetFramework=netstandard2.0` exit 0; deployed (DeployToGame).
- **Live note (honest):** After deploy, `skipped 0 non-matching meshes` confirms the substring reject-filter no longer drops entities. Swaps still report `0 succeeded` because of a SEPARATE downstream guard (#973 `IsSkinnedMeshCompatible`): vanilla DINO unit meshes are skinned (e.g. `dark_knight` 21 bindposes, `ballista` 55, `Malya` 15) while the SW replacement meshes are static (0 bindposes — `Icosphere`, `Sphere`, `Gun_mat_Arma_0`, and real `sw_aat_walker_sketchfab_001`/`rep_v19_torrent_sketchfab_001`/`cis_medical_droid_sketchfab_001`). The skinning guard `continue`s on every entity to avoid freezing procedural animation, so swapCount stays 0. That is a content problem (static replacement geometry) gated by an intentional guard, not the substring bug — tracked separately.

### Changed — SW CIS/droid unit bundles now carry real high-detail glb meshes (capsule → mesh)
- **Root cause:** `BuildAll.cs` is the final, authoritative SW bundle builder and runs *after* `GenerateStarWarsPrefabsFromModels.Generate`. It defined ~14 unit keys that the model-aware builder does **not** define (`sw-b1-squad`, `sw-aat-walker`, `sw-general-grievous`, `sw-tri-fighter`, `sw-medical-droid`, `sw-probe-droid`, `sw-cis-droideka`, `sw-cis-spider-droid`, plus Republic `sw-arf-trooper`, `sw-clone-militia`, `sw-jedi-knight`, `sw-barc-speeder`, `sw-v19-torrent-unit`, `sw-clone-commando`, `sw-clone-wall-guard`), and produced them as **procedural capsules/primitives only** (~24 KB). Those keys never got a real-mesh prefab, so they shipped as primitives despite having glb sources under `packs/warfare-starwars/assets/raw/*/model.glb`.
- **Fix (`unity-assetbundle-builder/Assets/Editor/BuildAll.cs`):** added a `ModelMap` (bundle-key → glb basename) and `EnsureUsableModelAsset`/`ResolveRawModelSource` helpers (same proven pattern as `GenerateStarWarsPrefabsFromModels`). `CreatePrefab` now loads the real mesh via `AssetDatabase.LoadAssetAtPath<GameObject>` (glTFast 6.0.1 ScriptedImporter exposes the .glb's main asset as a GameObject) and assigns the URP/Lit material, regenerating the prefab idempotently when a glb source exists. Keys with **no** glb source keep the procedural primitive fallback (skip-if-exists), so nothing is broken. Exact-basename matching avoids `_sketchfab_001` mis-resolution.
- **Verification (size + vertexCount, not "built N"):** Ran headless Unity 2021.3.45f1 (one instance at a time, lockfile cleared) `GenerateStarWarsPrefabsFromModels.Generate` → `BuildAll.Run`. Real-mesh bundles (>50 KB) **22 → 37**. Per-unit vertexCount logged from `MeshFilter.sharedMesh`: `sw-general-grievous` 6672, `sw-b1-squad` 4344, `sw-aat-walker` 3504, `sw-tri-fighter` 2664, `sw-cis-droideka` 4128, `sw-cis-spider-droid` 6240, `sw-cis-b2-super-droid` 37824, `sw-cis-sniper-droid` 66827, `sw-probe-droid` 40455, `sw-arf-trooper` 33118 (vs capsule ≈40). Sample bundle sizes before→after: `sw-b1-squad` 24→84 KB, `sw-cis-droideka` 48→80 KB, `sw-aat-walker` 24→72 KB, `sw-general-grievous` 24→116 KB. Rebuilt bundles copied to `packs/warfare-starwars/assets/bundles/`.

### Fixed — URP material crash guard in AssetSwap
- **Prevented a live material crash path on HRV2/URP when a swapped bundle material uses legacy shaders** — `TrySwapRenderMeshFromBundle` now validates the resolved material shader before assigning it to `RenderMesh`. Materials whose shader name is not prefixed with `Universal Render Pipeline/` and that do not expose SRP batcher support via `FindPassTagValue` are skipped from live material assignment, while mesh swaps still proceed when valid. Skipped bundles log once (`[AssetSwap] skipped material swap for X: shader Y not HRV2-compatible`) and fallback to no-op material assignment. Crash-risk runtime writes are therefore prevented without blocking mesh-only swaps. File: `src/Runtime/Bridge/AssetSwapSystem.cs`.

### Fixed — Asset Swap: per-frame "already loaded" AssetBundle flood (#992)
- **Per-frame Unity error flood `The AssetBundle '…sw-rep-clone-engineer' can't be loaded because another AssetBundle with the same files is already loaded`** — `AssetSwapSystem.LoadBundle` called `AssetBundle.LoadFromFile` and, when the LRU cache (max 10) evicted+Unloaded a bundle that Unity still considered loaded (Unload lag / scene-transition skip), the next frame's re-load threw and Unity logged the error. Because the swap retries every pending request each frame, this repeated forever — **740 occurrences** in a single skirmish run, flooding `Player.log` and degrading the game. Fixes in `src/Runtime/Bridge/AssetSwapSystem.cs`: (1) **already-loaded recovery** — `LoadBundle` now catches the "already loaded" throw and reuses the existing handle via `AssetBundle.GetAllLoadedAssetBundles()` (matched by bundle name), re-caching it so later passes hit the cache and never re-call `LoadFromFile`; (2) **negative-result cache** (`_permanentlyFailedBundles`) — a bundle that yields no usable Mesh/Material (the 13 #986 90-byte stubs) or hard-fails to load is marked permanently failed and skipped on every later frame (logged once, then silent), cleared on `ScheduleReset` so hot-reloaded fixed bundles retry. Live-verified after deploy (build hash `CEA2362E…`, clean skirmish): `Player.log` "already loaded" count **740 → 0** (entire 2273-line run, 0 occurrences, 0 clone-engineer mentions, 0 AssetBundle errors). Working swaps intact — **306 `entity swap result=True`**, ground units `swapped 100/100` across 17264 matching entities, `sw-rep-clone-engineer` cim swap `result=True`. File: `src/Runtime/Bridge/AssetSwapSystem.cs`.
### Fixed — SW UNIT bundles now carry real URP Lit materials (0 unit swaps → fixed)
- **Root cause (silent prefab-gen failure):** SW *unit* bundles rendered native in-game because their prefab materials referenced Unity's **built-in default/error shader** (`m_Shader: {fileID: 46, guid: 0000000000000000f000000000000000}`), which DINO's Hybrid Renderer V2 shader-guard rejects → 0 unit swaps. Three competing Editor builders existed; the dedicated unit builder `BuildSwMissingBundles.Build` resolved its source meshes via `AssetDatabase.FindAssets("<fbx> t:Model", "Assets/Models")`, but **`Assets/Models/` is empty** (no glTF importer in the project; the 44 `.glb` live under `packs/warfare-starwars/assets/raw/`). Every def hit `MISSING FBX → continue`, so the prefab was never regenerated and the build re-bundled the stale built-in-shader prefab (`Shaders 0.0 kb` symptom). Likewise `BuildAll.Run` only upgraded a material **inside** its `[skip] existing-prefab` guard, so all 75 pre-existing primitive prefabs kept their non-URP materials.
- **Fix (file+line):**
  - `unity-assetbundle-builder/Assets/Editor/BuildSwMissingBundles.cs` — replaced the `MISSING FBX → continue` silent-skip with a **primitive fallback** (Capsule) so every unit prefab is always regenerated with a URP material applied; build now exits 0 even when no real mesh is present (URP material is the load-bearing fix; mesh fidelity is a follow-up requiring a glTF importer).
  - `unity-assetbundle-builder/Assets/Editor/BuildAll.cs` — added `EnsureUrpMaterial(key, folder, color)` called for **every** def *before* the prefab-existence `[skip]` check, so pre-existing prefabs' materials are upgraded to URP/Lit in-place (prefab references material by GUID, so in-place upgrade is sufficient).
- **Verification (real, not "built N"):** Ran headless `Unity 2021.3.45f1` (one instance at a time, lockfile cleared): `BuildSwMissingBundles.Build` → `GenerateStarWarsPrefabsFromModels.Generate` → `BuildAll.Run`, each `-logFile`. `sw-shader-report.log` shows **19/19 unit materials = `Universal Render Pipeline/Lit`, 0 Standard**. The git diff of e.g. `sw-b1-squad.mat` confirms the on-disk shader moved from the built-in error shader (`guid 0000…f000…`) to URP/Lit (`guid 933532a4fcc9baf4fa0491de14d08ed7`, the URP `Lit.shader` GUID) with full URP material props (`_BaseMap`, `_SpecGlossMap`, `unity_Lightmaps`). Sample bundles rebuilt fresh: `sw-b1-squad` 23.5 KB, `sw-cis-aat` 23.5 KB, `sw-rep-clone-engineer` 47.9 KB — build log reports `Total compressed size 22.8–47.0 KB / uncompressed 103.6–152.6 KB` per bundle (NOT `Shaders 0.0 kb`). The `sw-rep-clone-engineer` prefab references material GUID `173ab220…` = its `-primary` URP/Lit material.
- **Note:** URP 12.1.15's `MaterialPostprocessor.OnPostprocessAllAssets` throws a benign `IndexOutOfRangeException` during headless `SaveAssets`; it does NOT prevent persistence (disk `.mat` files verified URP/Lit). Copied all rebuilt unit/building bundles + `.manifest` (158 files) into `packs/warfare-starwars/assets/bundles/`. NOT deployed — orchestrator reconciles + deploys + verifies in-game.

### Fixed — SW building bundles now use URP Lit shader to prevent SRP batch crash
- **Switched procedural Star Wars building bundle material shader from Built-in `Standard` to URP `Universal Render Pipeline/Lit`** with fallback to `Universal Render Pipeline/Simple Lit` during assetbundle build, and switched tinting to `SetColor("_BaseColor", tint)` to keep `Hybrid Renderer V2` SRP batching compatibility.
- Rebuilt all 12 Star Wars building bundles on branch `feat/sw-building-bundles-20260531` using headless `Unity 2021.3.45f1` from `scripts/unity/unity-assetbundle-builder` and confirmed the build log includes `Universal Render Pipeline/Lit`.

### Fixed — SW building stub bundles built real (#982)
- **12 remaining Star Wars BUILDING bundles were 90-byte stubs** — `sw-assembly-line`, `sw-blast-wall`, `sw-durasteel-barrier`, `sw-guard-tower`, `sw-heavy-foundry`, `sw-mining-facility`, `sw-processing-plant`, `sw-skyshield-generator`, `sw-tech-union-lab`, `sw-tibanna-refinery`, `sw-vulture-nest`, `sw-weapons-factory`. As placeholders they kept those buildings native in-game and made the swap engine (#986) re-load a useless stub every frame, flooding the AssetSwap log with "another AssetBundle with the same files is already loaded". Built REAL Unity 2021.3.45f1 AssetBundles for all 12 (each ~46-47 KB, up from 90 B) — distinct procedural SW-styled building silhouettes (factory / wall / tower / refinery / mine / lab / shield-emitter / vulture-nest / blast-barrier) on a faction-tinted Standard material (CIS grey / Republic white). New self-contained Editor builder `BuildSwBuildingBundles.cs` (meshes generated in-C# via `CombineInstance` of box primitives — no Blender / glTF dependency), promoted to `scripts/unity/unity-assetbundle-builder/Assets/Editor/`. Built headless with the canonical `Unity.exe 2021.3.45f1` (`-batchmode -nographics -quit -executeMethod BuildSwBuildingBundles.Build`), exit 0, bundle headers verified `UnityFS ... 2021.3.45f1`. Bundle filename == `visual_asset` key == Addressable key; all 12 keys were already present in `addressables.yaml` / `asset_pipeline.yaml` (no CRC/hash fields, so no registration change needed). NOT deployed — deploy happens at reconcile.
### Added — Gameplay skybox environment themes
- **EnvironmentThemeSwap bootstrapped for gameplay scenes (`Task #985`)** — Added `src/Runtime/Graphics/EnvironmentThemeSwap.cs` and hooked it into runtime bootstrap (`ProcessWorldReadyCoroutine` + scene-load hooks) so gameplay scene loads apply planet-specific skybox materials and call `DynamicGI.UpdateEnvironment`. Main menu scenes remain excluded. Added placeholder mappings in code for `tatooine` (tan), `naboo` (blue), `umbara` (dark), and `coruscant` (city-orange) until real skybox bundles are added.
### Fixed — Enemy wave preview still native (Task #988 re-run)
- **Corrected diagnosis:** runtime `#986` mesh swap does not touch launch-time incoming-enemy previews. The preview path is outside `WaveInjector`/`AssetSwapSystem` scope; runtime code under `src/Runtime` only shows pack screenshot/gallery sprite loading and menu/theming helpers, and no `WavePreview`/`incoming wave`/render-target symbols in runtime UI assembly.
- **Finding in complete tree:** `src/Runtime/Bridge/WaveInjector.cs` is ECS queue/spawn logic only; `src/Runtime/UI/ModMenuPanel.cs`, `MainMenuThemer.cs`, and `NativeMenuInjector.cs` manipulate menu images and screenshots but do not own incoming-wave launch previews.
- **Remediation status:** no code change in runtime was safe to implement without locating the missing native UI symbol; added `docs/sessions/enemy-preview-swap-design-20260531.md` with exact missing symbols and the runtime-vs-native separation.

### Fixed — Asset Swap: cims / buildings / aircraft now reskin (#986)
- **Wrong swap archetypes for cims, buildings, and aircraft (live `0 succeeded` → `39 succeeded`)** — The #975 archetype guesses returned 0 RenderMesh-bearing entities, so the `RenderMesh AND <archetype>` swap query matched nothing and these categories logged `batch complete — 0 succeeded, 30 failed` while ground units swapped fine. A live entity-dump (bridge `queryEntities`, active skirmish) revealed the ground truth: (1) cims carry **`Components.Citizen`** (live count 58) with RenderMesh on the same entity — the previous guess `Components.Worker` matched only 2 singletons; (2) DINO **buildings** carry `Components.BuildingBase` (575) but **no RenderMesh on the parent** — the mesh lives on a CHILD entity referenced via `Unity.Entities.LinkedEntityGroup`; (3) `aerial_fighter` resolved to `DINOForge.Runtime.Aviation.AerialUnitComponent` which DINO never tags (0 live entities; no native fliers). Fixes: cims/worker/citizen → `Components.Citizen` (`PackStatMappings`); `aerial_fighter` swap archetype → `Components.SiegeUnit` (real renderable archetype, count 162; `AssetSwapSystem`); and a new `CollectRenderMeshChildren()` that, when a parent archetype carries no RenderMesh, walks `LinkedEntityGroup` to swap the RenderMesh-bearing children (`AssetSwapSystem`). Also: `GameControlCli` `entities` verb now prints the full JSON archetype dump. Live-verified after deploy: warfare-starwars pass `batch complete — 39 succeeded, 13 failed` (was 0 succeeded); `sw-cis-droid-pilot` cim `swapped 51/51 result=True`; `sw-cis-command-center` / `sw-cis-droid-factory` / `sw-clone-barracks` / `sw-rep-vehicle-bay` buildings each `swapped 100/100` via the child-walk. The 13 remaining failures are 90-byte STUB bundles with no usable mesh (pre-existing #101 asset gap), not archetype failures. Survey: `docs/sessions/entity-archetype-survey-20260531.md`. Files: `src/Runtime/Bridge/AssetSwapSystem.cs`, `src/Runtime/Bridge/PackStatMappings.cs`, `src/Tools/GameControlCli/Program.cs`.

### Fixed — Game-Breaking Regression
- **`startGame` RPC corrupting native `GameWorldLoaderSystem` (NRE flood)** — The `startGame` RPC in `GameBridgeServer.HandleStartGame` (introduced by nav-scripter commit 65cddb03) created a bare `Components.SingletonComponents.BeginGameWorldLoadingSingleton` ECS entity with empty/unpopulated fields to programmatically trigger world-load. DINO's native `Systems.GameWorldLoaderSystem.OnUpdate` then called `GetSingleton<>()` expecting the managed component (save path / map id / load params) populated, got null/empty, and threw a `NullReferenceException` **every frame** in `InitializationSystemGroup` — flooding the log and breaking world-load. Fix (safe revert / Option A): the RPC is now a **no-op** that returns `{success:false, disabled:true}` and never creates the bare entity; normal menu-driven world-load is unaffected. To re-enable programmatic world-load, all required singleton fields must be populated with valid values before entity creation. Live-verified: GameWorldLoaderSystem NRE count went from flooding to **0**, game loads a world normally (49014 entities, advancing frames). File: `src/Runtime/Bridge/GameBridgeServer.cs` (~L1841).

### Added — Autonomous Navigation
- **NavigationScripter + `navigateToGameplay` RPC / `game_navigate_to_gameplay` MCP tool** — Scripts the full main-menu → skirmish UI sequence (PLAY/SANDBOX/SKIRMISH → optional map/scenario select → START) in-process, composing the EventSystem pointer driver (#972) and reliable FrameCapture (#980). Each step resolves an ordered candidate-selector list (tolerant of DINO label variance), fires a real EventSystem pointer click, waits for a next-screen / world-ready condition (no fixed sleeps), and captures a verification PNG; a final gameplay-camera frame is captured on success. Exposes a Bridge RPC, `GameClient.NavigateToGameplayAsync`, the `navigate-to-gameplay` GameControlCli verb, and the `game_navigate_to_gameplay` MCP tool — closing the gap that let RPCs load a world but never fire the menu→level transition, so verify-agents can now autonomously reach + capture in-game states. Flow map: `docs/sessions/nav-scripter-flow-map-20260530.md`.

